Part 1:
For the EV dataset, I propose using a composite row key of Make#Model#DOL_Vehicle_ID (for example, TESLA#MODEL 3#253586308). Bigtable stores data in lexicographical order, 
so by using Make as the first component of the row key, we leverage the natural variety in manufacturers, such as Tesla, Nissan, and Chevrolet, to distribute writes across 
different tablets. This approach avoids hotspotting, which could occur if a low-cardinality or sequential key like Model Year were used; in that scenario, all writes for new 
2024 vehicles would target a single node, overwhelming it while other nodes remain idle. Queries by Make are highly efficient because the prefix allows for a simple prefix 
scan, enabling retrieval of all records for a specific manufacturer (e.g., all Tesla vehicles). In contrast, queries by City are inefficient since City is not part of the 
row key; locating relevant rows would require a full table scan. In a production environment, this could be addressed by creating a secondary index table with a row key such 
as City#DOL_Vehicle_ID.

For column families, I recommend grouping the 16 dataset attributes into three logical families: Specs, Location, and Registration. Specs includes Model Year, Electric 
Vehicle Type, CAFV Eligibility, and Electric Range, capturing the technical characteristics of each vehicle. Location contains County, City, State, Postal Code, Legislative 
District, Vehicle Location, and 2020 Census Tract, representing all geographic metadata. Registration includes Electric Utility, DOL Vehicle ID, and VIN, covering 
administrative and utility-tracking information. Bigtable stores each column family in separate physical files (SSTables), so if a query only requires technical data, 
such as calculating the average Electric Range by Model Year, the system reads only the Specs column family and can skip Location and Registration data entirely, 
significantly reducing disk I/O and speeding up analytical queries.

Regarding horizontal scaling, there is a trade-off between hashed and range-based shard keys. A hashed shard key on VIN ensures near-perfect data distribution across 
the cluster. Even if 10,000 Teslas are added simultaneously, their hashed VINs are scattered across nodes, preventing any single node from becoming a bottleneck. However, 
this approach sacrifices range-scan capability, making it impossible to efficiently retrieve all vehicles with VINs in a specific interval. Conversely, a range-based shard 
key on Model Year preserves the physical ordering of records, allowing fast sequential reads for queries like “all vehicles from 2015 to 2020.” The downside is severe 
hotspotting, as new data predominantly belongs to the current Model Year, potentially overwhelming a single node and degrading overall cluster performance.

